segments.text: So he kind of had two conflicting things going at once.
One, he was trying to enlarge the service component of the department.
And to this end, he hired technical writing people.
However, he was also, in a less pronounced way,
trying to expand the literary offerings.
And we did acquire a bunch of good people when he was head.
From what institutions?
Oh, gee, I don't know.
Were these new PhDs?
These were new PhDs, and they were from all over.
Naturally, we have always had a bunch of people from UT,
but they came from all over the country.
And as far as you were aware, did we begin to be competitive?
In our beginning salaries for these new...
I can't say because I only have a sense of what we were offering
as opposed to what other places were offering.
But I would say, yes, we could not have brought some of these people here
if we hadn't been offering what other places were offering.
And the graduate program, how was it changing?
It was getting better students.
It was getting more and better students.
This is what I want to see more of even now.
The master's program was developing as a separate entity,
which it should be.
And I think that recently we've kind of sacrificed the master's program
to the PhD program.
We don't have that many students coming through anymore
getting masters and finding jobs.
And I want to see this.
If we have to offer a degree in professional writing or something,
I'd like to see us get back our master's program.
Were there any opportunities missed back there in the 80s?
Some things that could have been done that weren't?
For one thing, we did not have much in the way of multiculturalism at all.
I'm sure that opportunities were missed there.
Lately, there's been a lot of cross-disciplinary action.
But we could have done that earlier, and some of us tried to,
and it was frowned on.
It was very hard to, for instance, get something going,
teach something, or get a pair of courses going.
Can you give an example of one that you or someone attempted to?
Oh, I remember attempting to start an adolescent psychology
and the adolescent novel course,
and the hurdles seemed just too great to pursue that project.
I don't remember how far we got with it,
but it looked as though this just couldn't be done.
And so maybe it could have if we pushed it,
but we didn't.
What became your normal routine of teaching?
What courses?
Well, I slipped into creative writing,
because that's what I've always been most interested in.
Oh, I guess I first had the chance to teach that about 12 years ago,
and there has been more and more demand for it.
The core curriculum allows some people, like in education,
to take it as a quasi-requirement.
That is, they have the choice.
They have the choice of creative writing or some other things.
And we just divided it into poetry and prose
instead of just teaching it all together,
and it really took off.
Now, for instance, this semester I have exclusively creative writing classes.
How many?
Two.
But two creative writing classes makes for a lot of work,
because each ego is involved.
It's teaching more to teach two creative writing classes,
than it is to teach more students in a lit class,
because lit students, you're not grating their souls.
So my normal routine now is teaching creative writing and women's novels.
And these are both upper-level undergraduate?
No, they can be either lower level.
For instance, one of my creative writing classes is 226,
which is essentially a sophomore-level class.
It will have freshmen in it, too, because they place out of the freshman class.
About how many per session?
Twenty-five.
And then the, let's see, you mentioned another,
other than creative writing, you mentioned another?
Women's novels.
Women's novels.
I have either 45 or 35 in there, depending on which level it is.
And that's upper level?
That's upper level.
It's either 374 or 474.
In that course, what are your favorite novels that you urge them to read?
Okay, we read Sylvia Plath's The Bell Jar.
We read Maxine Hung Kingston's Woman Warrior.
We read Toni Morrison's Beloved.
Let's see, what else?
We read Kate Chopin's The Awakening.
Very often we start with Jane Eyre, because I always teach it the same way.
I teach it as The Buildings Roman, which is the novel of development or education.
And so I use only novels which show either coming of age
or a learning experience of some other kind.
Okay.
Any other point in life?
Mm-hmm.
So often we use as our basic example that Jane Eyre,
and then proceed through more contemporary ones up until the latest ones.
And for you, you are now one of, how many women on the faculty in English?
A lot.
I would say that the faculty is about half male, half female.
Mm-hmm.
I don't know and are they are there some minority also yes we have quite a few
now we have let's see we've got peaches Henry coming in she's she's on some sort
of odd fellowship for this year but it was her first name peaches I thought you
said peaches peaches Henry and we hired her away from Notre Dame we've got okay
Kamla duty that's new she's a visiting assistant professor we have Kimberly
Brown let's see now that's two of Kimberly Brown all these are
african-americans can't remember his name we have four five if you count
peaches I believe african-american faculty and then we have Marco Patel is I
it kind of surprises me a little that we are not able to get and keep many
Hispanics faculty we have had better luck with african-americans and I don't really
understand that because here we are but I guess they don't want to come to
College Station compare the students now and the students then okay now there are
students I get students from all cultures at least I get about an equal
balance of male and female students maybe even a few more women students
because I teach poetry writing the fiction people get a few more men
the students are less likely to do what I say they don't call me ma'am they're
more likely to what what do they call you they call me Professor McCann or Dr.
McCann okay I actually I'd like to encourage my graduate students to call me
by my first name but they don't do it they they're more intellectually involved many of them
they they're more intellectually involved many of them
But I'm not teaching the same things.
And if I were teaching freshmen now, I might find them a lot, that is, they would be multicultural
and there would be a lot of women, but they too might think of the class as something
to be got through as opposed to something that they're passionately interested in.
People don't take creative writing unless they're interested.
So I don't have sleeping students the way I used to, but they would be very polite when
awakened back then.
What are their career goals today?
An awful lot of them want to teach.
Some of them want to teach in high schools.
My undergraduates, some of them want to teach in high schools, and I think that's great.
We certainly need people teaching in high schools.
Some of them want to teach in college.
Of course, my graduate students, people who are getting a PhD in English all want to teach
in college.
I don't have, when I get the women's novels class.
That is not for English majors necessarily.
And I get a lot of people there, a lot of women who are going into business and industry.
I don't, they're going to be personnel managers.
I get a lot of psychology majors.
I get mostly women in those classes too, I would say five to one, because it's rare that
a man wants to sign up for all these women's coming-of-age novels, but I get a few.
As far as you're aware, in terms of...
Offices, salary, promotions, and so forth, have women been treated equitably in recent
years in the department?
Not really.
As far as offices and so forth, yes.
And I think Larry Mitchell makes a real effort at this.
But especially in the recent past, there's been quite a bit of discrimination against
women, I think.
And it takes funny forms.
There are a few women in high-profile positions, but I'm not sure they have real power.
But I know that efforts are being made.
Funny things happen.
For instance, here's an example.
There was some group that was supposed to study the situation, and the women's salaries
are not as high as the men's.
I mean, there's no question of that, if you look at the salaries for women, women full
professors, for instance.
Now, of course, there are various ways of looking at it.
There are ways of looking at the information.
If you look at them on a university-wide level, you get something like a $20,000 difference,
at least.
And then other people argue, well, the women are in liberal arts.
But of course, part of this is because the women were not really welcomed in those other
fields.
And it's still harder for a woman to get tenure in some of these other fields.
I mean, I look at what they did to Lynn Lamoureux.
That was a case where she was promised all kinds of things when she came out here, and
she got none of them.
And then they didn't give her tenure.
But of course, she got tenure, but she had to go through the legal system.
She was originally, she's now in another department, because when they tenured her, when they were
told by the law that they had to tenure her, or lose something major, they did, but they
stuck her in another department.
But I'm sure there's, if you want to look her up, her name is Lamoureux.
Now, in English, what about French?
French?
French is the same as English?
So, you are, as far as you know, about comparable salaries and promotions and so forth, men and
women?
I think they're about even in English.
I don't see real discrepancy.
And as far as you know, when there are recruitment opportunities that there is an effort to
be balanced and fair?
Oh, I don't think that, I don't think we even make that an issue anymore.
That is, I really think that people are looked at.
I don't think sex plays a role anymore.
anymore.
I think that we do have a balance.
We may have more women than men.
We brought
in some women.
We brought in Jen Swearengen, for instance, at a full professor level.
I
don't think that there's a problem with that.
Who, who, a knowledgeable outsider would know, recognize most, who, which faculty
in English would an outside, informed outsider know most about?
Who are the high, the highest
visibility faculty?
Margaret Ezell.
Ezell?
Yes.
In what area?
She is in British literature, and everybody knows her.
Outside of Margaret,
let's see, there are a whole bunch of people that are pretty well known, like Larry Reynolds
and, of course, Jerry Loving would go, I think, next to Margaret Ezell.
Jerry Loving.
What's his special?
American Lit, and he's got a very well-reviewed book about Walt Whitman out, and I would say
probably next to Margaret, the next person to be known would be Jerry.
He's written several
books on Whitman.
This one, though, is popular as well as scholarly, and he's been on all
the, he was interviewed all over the country by all of these major shows.
Let's see, who
else?
Larry, after Margaret and Jerry, then there would be Larry.
Bedford Clark is pretty
well known as a Warren scholar.
Robert Penn Warren, let's see, who else?
Well, Jan Swearengin
is known for her work in rhetoric.
I would say those are the people.
Do you have the impression that the department is making progress these days?
Is it getting
stronger, getting better?
Yeah, I think it is, actually.
I think it is.
We've lost a bunch of faculty members, but we've also brought in some very new ones,
and certainly in certain areas, we're making strides.
We are now extremely multicultural,
whereas six years ago, we were hardly multicultural at all.
Who deserves credit for that?
Larry Mitchell, I'd have to say.
He is definitely a head, not a chair, but he has, and I've
had a lot of differences with him, but he has, I think, I don't know, I don't know,
done a lot to make the department multicultural, fairer to women, and so forth.
About how many full-time tenure-track faculty are there now?
Fifty?
Sixty?
Or between sixty and seventy, I'd say.
Between sixty?
Yeah, but that's easy enough information to get in the main office.
I don't know it.
And does the department ever get together?
Yes and no.
Not, it gets together.
I'll tell you, I don't know.
I don't know.
I don't
know. I don't know. I don't know. I don't know. I don't know. I don't know.
I don't know. I don't know. I don't know. I don't know. I don't know. I don't know.
I don't know.
I don't know.
I don't know.
I don't know. I don't know. I don't know. I don't know.
But there is an annual party to welcome the graduate students, and I would say a third
of the faculty attend.
Larry Mitchell will have a party for the entire faculty.
Two-thirds
will attend that.
But it doesn't get together because these things are huge, crowded parties,
and you go and you grab your whatever and say hello to everybody and slither out the
other door because it's just too crowded for real conversation.
That is something that,
It's just hard to do, to have real conversations at parties and really get together with your
fellow faculty members.
How do you and your faculty friends from whatever department, how do you get together?
I would say that my faculty friends and I will have dinner together sometimes at one
another's homes.
I used to give parties, but I don't do it anymore, it seems too much hassle.
And there's more work, that is one problem, there is more work, there are more meetings
People get so they just want to get a shot of all of this.
They don't want to take it home.
But when we do get together, we get together for dinner.
All right, so you're saying that compared to 20, 30 years ago, you're working harder.
Are the students working harder?
No, they're working about the same amount.
About the same.
How would you compare the capability of the student's performance today?
Who gets an A or a B with one who got an A or a B 20, 30 years ago?
I would say that the gentleman's C is now the gentleman's B.
B?
Yeah.
What I would like to see is the introduction of plus and minus grades so that you could
still distinguish among A's and B's because most of us in upper level courses, not only
throughout the College of Liberal Arts, but in other colleges too, most of the grades
are A's and B's.
So I would say that the student's A's and B's are not as high as they used to be.
But you're saying that that A or B doesn't require as much work as it used to?
I don't think it requires as high a level of competence, no, I don't.
I think that students that I gave C's to 30 years ago, many of them would now get B's.
And as the students are entering today, are they better prepared from high school than
they used to be?
No.
No, they're not.
They're not, huh.
Not certainly not in the area of writing skills, they could write better then.
What major issues do you think A&M should be concerned about today?
Okay, multiculturalism and fairness.
I don't know.
I know that we're working on it because we have a bunch of new faculty who are members
of minority groups, so we're working on it.
But I don't know.
More needs to be done with the students with this because a lot of students don't have
the message.
And yet it can't be done in the form of, I don't think, I don't know how this new program
is going to work where people have to take classes.
I don't know if this is going to fix things up or not.
But I do know something needs to be done because I see some basic racism around.
In a way, too, I think we need to.
Sometimes I think that some of the interest in cross-disciplinary work, multiculturalism
and so forth, is more cosmetic than real.
And I don't know how to make it more real, but I think it needs to be made more real.
All right.
Other?
For instance, if you'll turn it off, I'll give you a second.
All right.
Now we're talking about things that can be done today and some goals that A&M should
undertake.
I'm trying to think of other things besides multiculturalism.
There are a lot of initiatives that are being taken that, for instance, there's a lot of
movement toward cross-disciplinary work and collaboration.
I think we need to become more international and we're doing that.
Now what do you mean by international?
I think I know, but I want to be sure.
I mean.
I mean, I mean.
I mean, one of the things that's odd.
I don't know what some of the things that we're doing, like the
great options that we've had.
Oh, I think there are a lot of good options.
There are.
I think it should be required that everybody learn a second language.
If I could be the emperor, I would make that a baccalaureate degree requirement.
Yeah.
For the modern world.
And in fact, though, I think that we are taking steps in this direction,
but I think that, yes, we need to encourage everyone to become more aware of other cultures
and to learn about them.
I remember reading that report where somebody said something to the effect
that they couldn't send Aggies to New York, let alone to Japan, or something like that.
We need to make it so that Aggies can go anywhere and know how to behave.
Is there any school or program you can think of that we might use as a model?
Is there any institution that is?
I think we have to make up our own direction for this
because there are a lot of different things that work,
but they have to do with particular institutions.
I don't think that we could adopt somebody else's program.
What should the department's goals be?
The English department's goals?
Okay.
I think we should strengthen our master's program
and introduce an attractive professional writing program.
We should be willing to provide, help teachers in the high school get masters in English
because I think that we've got a situation kind of where the tail's wagging,
and the dog's wagging, and the dog's wagging, and the dog's wagging, and the dog's wagging, and the dog's wagging, and the dog's wagging, and the dog's wagging, and the dog's wagging.
with the Texas Education Association.
They're dictating to us what we should be teaching,
and they're not having the right, they don't have the right emphases.
I think we need to work on that.
I think we need to strengthen linguistics.
I think we need to strengthen creative writing.
I always thought that creative writing was a wonderful possibility
for bringing in multicultural people, but we've never done it.
We did have Gordon,
and we kind of,
we inherited him from theater arts.
He didn't come to us originally, I don't believe, I'm not sure,
but he was very definitely an asset while we had him.
And we could, for instance, since he died,
there's been nobody to teach playwriting.
We have this whole, we don't have a program in creative writing,
but we do have a track, and it's got a missing stare.
So this would be a wonderful opportunity to bring in a Hispanic or black playwright
but this won't happen, because our emphasis is very much on literary scholarship
of a particular sort, essentially theory.
And I think we need to, everybody else in the department will tell you differently,
but I think that we should focus less on theory and more on these other areas
so that we are a strong department across the board.
We don't just have strong theory contingent.
Your personal goals.
My personal goals.
Well, for my scholarship, you mean, or?
For your professional.
For my professional development, okay.
Well, I do anthologies.
I've done two of them with someone else, and I'm working on a third one myself.
I'd like to put together a really good anthology of poetry.
I also have my own poetry collections.
I'd like to get one of these published
by a well-known press.
Because so far I've only been able to interest small press in my work.
I have a kind of strange project that is a book of poetry based on letters.
I have a collection of letters.
I collect old letters.
And this is a collection of letters written by members of,
by the two halves of a courting couple in 1830.
And they get married.
And then they become family letters.
Somebody kept these letters that start actually in 1828
and end in 1863, I think is the last one.
And I've done poems that are dramatic monologues based on these letters.
And I'm also trying to fill some history in.
Some of the groups that they refer to,
some of the journals and so forth.
I'm trying to find out more information about these
to put little historical bridges in.
And I want to get somebody interested in printing this.
It's fascinating.
The way you can see into this couple
from this perspective.
And how they lived because
they wrote meticulously detailed letters
of how they lived, what they had for lunch.
He was a schoolteacher who later became a Baptist minister, I believe.
After the sequence of letters was finished.
And most of the letters are actually from the courting period.
And it's just interesting to see what courtship
between very religious people was like at that time.
Of course I've got a lot of other letters from that time in my collection.
And religion, Christianity was very definitely
woven into the fabric of lives the way it is not now.
All decisions were referred to Providence.

He should be somebody who is going to be fair to all departments and not just the departments that he comes from.
He should be somebody who is familiar with interdisciplinary work in the direction of studying law.
He or she, and I'd like to say she of course, should be somebody who is interested in looking at how women are treated in the colleges.
I don't know.
My department, as I said, I don't see anything as fair.
However, I know people who have been treated very fairly in other departments.
So he should be able to kind of reset these switches in those departments.
From what kind of institution should he be reset?
I would say in a large space.
He wouldn't do well with somebody who had to deal with only small numbers of things.
Right now, you're advising the provost.
I don't even know what the provost does.
He's there.
What does he do?
If you tell me what he does, maybe I can make some suggestions.
What about the president?
Again, I don't know what their functions are.
What direction should the president lead this?
I think in the direction of increasing the number of faculty all across the board,
of reducing the number of large, this is done, I know, for financial reasons.
They have these huge courses.
I think these should be reduced to very few courses.
I think those should be only the most basic courses.
